  {
    "file": "frontend/src/components/runs/LiveRunProgress.tsx",
    "line": "126-129",
    "summary": "Cancel→poll race: optimistic cancelled status is overwritten back to 'running' by an in-flight/next poll, and polling resumes.",
    "failure_scenario": "User clicks Cancel on a running run. cancelRun resolves and onCancel optimistically sets progress.status='cancelled'. But the poll loop's `active` flag is still true and an in-flight getRunProgress (or the next scheduled tick) is still outstanding. Backend cancel is cooperative/best-effort (per the cancelRun docstring: 'may race a fast run to completion'), so the next progress payload still has status='running'. Line 106 setProgress(next) clobbers the cancelled state, line 108 sees non-terminal and line 109 reschedules another tick. Net effect: the Cancel button reappears, the status tag flips back to 'running', and polling never stops until the backend independently flips status — directly contradicting the line 127-128 comment that the in-flight poll 'will also resolve to it and stop.'"
  },
  {
    "file": "frontend/src/components/runs/LiveRunProgress.tsx",
    "line": "117-120",
    "summary": "Cleanup cancels only the pending timer, not an in-flight getRunProgress fetch; the `active` guard is the only protection and it is bypassable by the cancel path.",
    "failure_scenario": "On unmount/runId change, the cleanup sets active=false and clears timerRef, but an already-dispatched getRunProgress promise keeps running. The `active` check at line 105 prevents setState-after-unmount for the poll path, so unmount itself is safe. However there is no shared guard between onCancel and the poll loop: after cancel, the poll's in-flight promise still passes its own `active` check (component is still mounted) and proceeds to setProgress, which is the mechanism enabling the cancel-overwrite race. The fix (an abort/ignore flag set by onCancel, or checking terminal-from-cancel before rescheduling) is absent."
  },
